Executive Summary

In this project, Team C assessed VIP’s business problem and designed an analysis around three objectives that provides insights into trends/patterns specific to customer types and packages, recommended applications to VIP’s business, and potential topics and techniques for further analyses.

The business problem was defined by VIP’s database stores information on all customer transactions, and their need to understand the behaviors and segmentations of their customers in order to improve their customer share and marketing strategies. From this business problem, three objectives were identified as:

  • Objective 1: Identify patterns and/or trends in first-time and repeat purchases
  • Objective 2: Determine whether the sale of one (or more) product(s) impact(s) the sale of other products
  • Objective 3: Understand the life cycle behaviors of first-time and repeat customers

With these objectives, the team focused on analyzing sales data from VIP to gain insights into first-time and repeat purchases, the interplay between product sales, and the life cycle behaviors of these customers. To ensure the accuracy and reliability of the results, the team implemented a robust data cleaning and preparation process that involved preserving relevant data, handling missing values, condensing unique ones, and removing problematic or faulty data.

The project’s key findings identify similarities and differences in the monthly transactions by customer type, the topmost packages and package combinations for each customer type, and the distribution of time between purchases for those topmost packages.

To help VIP improve their customer share and marketing strategies, the team recommends changes and new ideas to the company’s strategies on discounts and marketing specific to each customer type. In addition, the team discusses limitations to our analysis as well as next steps for addressing those limitations and drilling into some of our more complex insights.

Data Preparation

The data cleaning section is a crucial component of any data analysis project. The quality of the data used for analysis significantly impacts the accuracy and reliability of the results. Therefore, it is essential to ensure that the data is consistent, complete, and error-free. This section describes the data cleaning process, which involves four primary areas, including preserving relevant data, handling missing values, condensing unique values, and removing problematic or faulty data. By following these steps, we aim to create a clean and robust dataset that builds a solid foundation for future analysis.

  1. Preserve the data between 10/01/2020 to 01/01/2023: In the follow-up interview with the clients, the team learned that all transactions predating October 1st, 2020, come from the old systems. Since the package identifications of old transactions did not translate to the new system, all old transactions are classified into only two packages: History and Shop. Due to the time constraint, the team assesses the project’s scope and determines to remove all transactions predating October 1, 2020, from our analysis.
  2. Handling missing values: The source dataset contained a significant number of missing values, which required multiple processes to either impute or remove the affected entries. To address this issue, a lookup table was created outside the original database, which enabled us to impute all missing town and state values and exclude wholesale store 30. The details of the cleaning steps are outlined in the following code block sections for reference purposes.
  3. Condensed unique package values: This project’s main focus is the package information and the original dataset contains over 328 different package names. The team member simplified the 328 unique Package Name values to 78 package focus areas to condense the package name information for more precise analysis. Additionally, after considering the needs of the clients, the team removed specific package entries, including “Shop” and “Standard Service.”
  4. Omit problematic and faulty data: Several problematic transactions were excluded from the final clean dataset, such as wholesale customer purchase history and those affiliated with the consolidated set of cash customers.

Analysis

Objective 1

Objective 1 aims to identify patterns and/or trends in first-time and repeat purchases. To start, we choose to analyze the count of transactions of first-time and repeat customers across the years. More specifically, we consider the breakdown of transactions by our two customer types: first-time and repeat customers. Recall from our data preparation that our analysis only considers data that was transferred from VIP Tires’ previous data management system to their newer one. Therefore, the data presented in all figures and analyses will represent transactions recorded between October 1, 2020 and December 31, 2022.

Figure 1

In Figure 1, the comparison of bar heights and compositions suggest that:

  • From 2021 to 2022, the total number of customer transactions stayed relatively flat, increasing only 2%.
  • In 2021 and 2022, roughly 75% of transactions were made by repeat customers.
  • There was 5.7% growth in First-time vs 0.7% growth in Repeat Customer Transactions

Figure 2 mainly presents the counts of transactions based on existing stores and new stores over the studied years. The new stores (store number 65-72) are those stores which just started operating since 2020. This is the information from the clients based on the store birthday information that was given as supplement material. Figure 2 answers the Question:

How do the opening of new stores since 2020 (65-72) impact the number of transactions by year and by customer type?

As complete package data is only available from October 2020, year-over-year comparison can only be made between 2021 and 2022; From Figures 2, we learn: * The count and breakdown of transactions by customers at existing stores was stable, even declining, from 2021 to 2022. * Of those transactions made at existing stores, 23% were made by new customers and 77% were made by repeat customers. * In 2021 and 2022, roughly 6% of transactions were made at new stores (and growing). * Of those transactions made at new stores, 33% were made by new customers and 67% were made by repeat customers.

  • Increase overall sales and customer retention.
  • Tailor their advertisements to incentivize customers to purchase them.
  • Can be used to inform product development decisions, such as introducing new packages that combine popular services or modifying existing packages to better align with customer preferences.

While the insights generated from Figure 7 are meaningful, their limitation to only four package categories is restrictive. For more comprehensive and quantitative insights, we turn to a Market Basket Analysis.

Market Basket Analysis

Part 1: Market Basket Analysis for All Customers

Market basket analysis can be performed for various purposes, and one of them is to understand the differences in customer purchase behavior in purchasing different packages. This study will perform market basket analysis to discover the correlation between the customer behavior and package purchase data. By examining the products that customers tend to purchase together, the clients would be able to identify patterns and associations that may not be immediately apparent from looking at individual transactions or customer profiles. Moreover, market basket analysis could increase the likelihood of repeat purchases and boost the revenue by suggesting related products to customer based on the previous packages purchase information, or even develop strategy to sell packages as a combination. When performing the analysis, the clients expressed the need to remove “Shop”, “PM” and “Standard Service” legacy packages, so this market basket does not include the mentioned 3 packages.

In market basket analysis, there are typically three main steps: data preparation, package frequency analysis, and rule generation using the Apriori algorithm.

In the data preparation step, the transactional data is cleaned and transformed to fit the requirements of the arules library in R Studio. This involves removing unwanted package names and separating each transaction into individual baskets, where each basket represents all the packages purchased in a single transaction.

The next step is to analyze the frequency of each package in the data set. This is done by visualizing the frequency distribution using an absolute package frequency plot. This plot shows how often each package was purchased and can help identify which packages got the most attention in the customers purchase history.

The final step is to generate rules using the Apriori algorithm. This algorithm is used to identify which packages tend to be purchased together and to generate association rules based on the frequency and co-occurrence of these packages. Two important concepts in this step are support and confidence. Support indicates the percentage of the transactions that the combination of item A and item B shows up in a combination. Confidence represents the transaction that purchase item A but also has item B. In general, the default values for minimum support is 0.1, and minimum confidence is 0.8, which is the rule being used in this analysis.

Part 2: Market Basket Analysis for first-time and repeat customers

The previous market basket analysis focused on understanding the purchasing patterns of all customers. The second part of this market basket analysis will mainly compare the purchasing behavior between first-time and repeat customers. By performing this comparison, VIP Tires could introduce package combos or service suggestions based on whether it is the customer’s first visit to the store. Moreover, this analysis would assist the market analysis team in developing strategies to convert first-time customers into potential long-term, loyal customers. Since every customer has a unique identification number, we are able to determine whether the customers are repeat customers by summing up the unique transaction amount.

While the package category with the highest absolute frequency is Tire Package, all top 10 rules with the highest confidence measures include Alignment on either the RHS or LHS. * First-time customers tend to focus on purchasing the Tire Package, prioritizing product purchases over services. * Alignment identified as the second most frequent package and found on the RHS for 80% of these top 10 rules. When Alignment is not on the RHS, it presents on the LHS. * Alignment and Other Vehicle Inspection has high association with most of the shopping patterns in the top 10 rules. * Rule 7 indicates that 96.47% of transactions where first-time customers bought Tie-Rod Replace, they also bought Alignment. {Tie-Rod Replace -> Alignment} has good 0.7 % support, high 96.3% confidence, and good 4.21 lift. These figures suggest that there is a high probability that customers will follow this shopping pattern, and the pattern is supported by a significant transaction count.

The figures for first-time customers show that the most popular package purchased from VIP Tires is the “Tire Package,” followed by “Alignment,” “State Inspection,” and “Oil change.” On the other hand, repeat customers are more likely to purchase the “Oil change,” “State Inspection,” and “Alignment” packages, with “Tire Package” being the fourth most frequent purchase. These frequency results are consistent with the analysis of all customers. This suggests that most first-time customers are more likely to come to the store to purchase tires, while repeat customers return for additional services provided by the company.

Objective 3

Ojective (3) is to understand the life cycle behaviors of first-time and repeat customers.

After studying the top absolute frequencies and rules in our Market Basket analysis, we want to understand how those results might depend on the typical duration for each package category.

knitr::opts_current$set(eval = TRUE)
package_colors_10 <- c("#9AC0CD","#6E8898FF","#2E5266FF","#5F4B8BFF","#A13941FF","#E3170AFF","#E95C20FF","#DAA03DFF","#006B38FF","#8FBC8F")

#calculate total lifetime and previous visits
visits <- df1 %>%
  filter(repeat_customer == "Yes") %>%
  filter(PackageFocus != "Shop") %>% 
  filter(PackageFocus != "PM") %>%
  filter(PackageFocus != "Standard Service") %>% 
  group_by(PackageFocus, CustomerId, Date) %>%
  tally(sort=FALSE) %>%
  rename(TotalPackagesPerVisit = n) %>%
  mutate(TotalPreviousVisits = row_number()-1) %>% 
  mutate(TotalLifetimeVisits = max(TotalPreviousVisits)+1)

#total transactions by repeat customers for any package
total_trans <- length(df1$PackageFocus)

#reference to top 10 packages for repeat customers
top_10_packages_repeat_df <- visits %>%
  group_by(PackageFocus) %>% 
  summarize(TotalPackages = n()) %>%  
  arrange(desc(TotalPackages)) %>%
  slice(1:10)
  
top_10_packages_repeat <- unique(top_10_packages_repeat_df$PackageFocus)

#calculate days between visits for top 10 packages for repeat customers
days_between_visits <- visits %>%
  filter(PackageFocus %in% top_10_packages_repeat) %>%
  filter(TotalLifetimeVisits > 1) %>% 
  mutate(DaysBetweenVisits = 
           ifelse(TotalPreviousVisits == 0, "N/A",
                  Date - lag(Date)))

#remove the row with the first date (as that has N/A value for days between visits)
#and conver the days between visits column to integers
days_between_visits_excl_first_date <- days_between_visits %>% 
  filter(DaysBetweenVisits != "N/A") %>% 
  mutate(DaysBetweenVisits = as.integer(DaysBetweenVisits))

perc_of_total_trans <- days_between_visits_excl_first_date %>% 
  group_by(PackageFocus) %>% 
  summarize(Perc_Trans = round(n()/total_trans*100))


#calculate the median number of days between visits 
median_days_between_visits <- days_between_visits_excl_first_date %>% 
  group_by(PackageFocus) %>% 
  summarize(median_duration = round(median(DaysBetweenVisits),1),
            total_repeats = sum(TotalPreviousVisits)) %>% 
  arrange(desc(median_duration))

#create box plot of days between visits by package focus area
days_between_visits_excl_first_date$PackageFocus <- factor(days_between_visits_excl_first_date$PackageFocus, levels=median_days_between_visits$PackageFocus)
days_between_visits_excl_first_date %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = PackageFocus, y = DaysBetweenVisits, fill=PackageFocus)) +
  geom_boxplot(outlier.shape = 1,outlier.alpha = 0.1, outlier.color="#6E6E6DFF") + 
  coord_flip() +
  labs(y = "Time between Purchase (Days)", x = "Package Category") +
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  ggtitle("Figure 11: Time between Purchases of Top 10 Packages for Repeat Customers") +
  scale_fill_manual(values=package_colors_10) +
  theme_light()

Figure 11 does just that by comparing the boxplots of those durations, and ranking those according to their median duration. From this, we learn:

  • The median time between repeat visits is shortest for Other Vehicle Inspection, Flat Repair, Oil Change, and Brakes packages.
  • This is not surprising for Oil Change, which has the highest number of transactions by repeat customers
  • This is surprising for Other Vehicle Inspection and Flat Repair, which have the two lowest count of transactions by repeat customers
  • With these surprising results, as well as some expected ones, we conclude the duration between visits impacts the frequencies and combinations for some packages, but not others.

Key Findings and Recommendations

All of this analysis has led to some meaningful findings:

  • Monthly transactions for first-time and repeat customers shared some lows (in February) and highs (in November-December), and complemented each other in the remaining months of the year. Relative to their 2021 transactions, first-time customers’ transactions worsened/improved in H1/H2 while repeat customer transactions did just the opposite.
  • In terms of absolute frequency for all 2020-2022 transactions, first-time and repeat customers shared the same top 4 package categories: Tire Package, State Inspection, Oil Change, and Alignment. However, the Tire Package led for first-time customers while the three services led for repeat customers. These top 4 package categories for repeat customers are rather surprising given the median duration between repeat purchases of all top 10 package categories.
  • In terms of combined packages, first-time customers most frequently combined Alignment with Tire-Rod Replace and other packages. Repeat customers most frequently combined service-related packages with Alignment and/or Other Vehicle Inspection packages.

With these findings, we’d like to propose a few recommendations to VIP:

  • For first-time customers, offering a discount on their next service if they purchase a Tire Package, or a discount on their purchase if they combine Alignment and Tire-Rod Replace packages
  • For repeat customers, considering the timing and package of their last purchase and the average duration between visits for that package; if timing of multiple packages align, offer discounts for a combination of those packages
  • Learning from the promotions and advertisements received by first-time and repeat customers in the months where transactions counts were especially high or low
  • Brainstorming special discounts and/or events to increase both first time and repeat customers in February
  • Evaluating the pricing and quality of service provided for top absolute and combination packages, especially those with surprisingly shorter/longer median durations between repeat purchases
  • Investing in further analysis of customer transactions

Next Steps

Next steps should consider the following:

  • The tires replacement cycle is generally 30,000 to 60,000 miles; meanwhile, brakes should be inspected every 20,000 to 30,000 miles or 1-2 years, with brake pads lasting 40,000 to 70,000 miles. The United States Department of Transportation Federal Highway Administration reports that the average driver traveled 12,724 miles in 2020, down from 14,263 average annual miles in 2019; therefore, a data range of 3-6 years would be necessary to examine the repurchase habits of a single customer with a single car. 2.25 years of data needed to be expanded.
  • Because of this knowledge, one of our team members focused on assigning PackageFocus from History based on SKU, Descriptions and the KPI data table previously provided and has recently completed a “key table” which will be provided to VIP to support future efforts to extend the start of the data set from Q4 2020 back to Q4 2017 (or earlier). While time constraints prevented the team from integrating this advance into our analysis, VIP may find the information useful in taking the analysis further.
  • Given the limited loyalty and vehicle data and the only customer demographic data being zip code, the team considered how to utilize the available data. Loyalty Program, Vehicle, Customer Zip Code and Store geospatial data has also been provided for use in any subsequent regression and categorization analyses. Proposals included considering the distance between VIP’s stores and population centers and the vehicle, economic and competition demographics of customer zip codes as factors in regression and classification analysis. Search, social media and credit-card processing-based analytics data may provide other interesting external datasets to supplement internal data.

To further our exploration of Objective (1), VIP might consider other measures and graphs that would help their analysts understand the life cycle behaviors of first-time and repeat customers, such as:

  • Categorize customers into bins according to Total Lifetime Visits, and analyze seasonality and volume of monthly sales separately.
  • Investigate the impact of new store openings on the lifecycle and behaviors for new customers
  • Conduct a deeper dive into Q4 sales for new customers.

To further VIP’s exploration of Objective (2), they might consider expanding on the team’s focus on:

  • Examine specific packages focus areas, such as the ones that are sold the most, sold the least, or sold differently across repeat and first-time customers.
  • Regression/Classification comparing Tire Package-purchasing Customers vs. non-Tire Customers.
  • Assess seasonality of sales by month and/or quarter by key package focus areas.
  • Compare packages sold by store location to look at local market differences.

To further explore Objective (3), VIP might consider building upon the team’s work to identify:

  • Identify relationships between packages in the same transaction AND sold in subsequent transactions.
  • Categorize customers (ex. Commercial/Fleet vs Household) & conduct in-depth analysis.
